deviceSlots.deviceName: HP NC532m Dual Port Flex-10 10GbE Multifunction BL-c Adapter
QLogic QMH2462 4Gb FC HBA for HP c-Class BladeSystem

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Advanced Memory Protection provides additional memory protection 
beyond ECC (error checking and correcting).
 
Advanced ECC provides the largest memory capacity to the
operating system.
 
Online Spare memory will allow a system to automatically map out 
a group of memory that is receiving excessive correctable memory 
errors. This memory will be replaced by a spare group of memory.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Advanced Memory Protection

options.name: Online Spare with Advanced ECC Support

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Assigns the logical COM Port number and associated
default resources to the selected physical serial port
This setting may be overwritten by your OS.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Embedded Serial Port

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Assigns the logical COM Port address and associated
default resources to be used by the Virtual Serial Port (VSP).
The VSP allows the ILO Management Controller to appear as
a physical serial port in order to support BIOS
Serial Console and Operating Systems serial console.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Virtual Serial Port

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
USB Enabled: enables all USB ports and embedded devices.
External USB Ports Disabled: only external USB ports are disabled.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: USB Control

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the user to prevent the system from booting
all USB devices connected to the server. This option will also 
disable booting iLO virtual media.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: USB Boot Support

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the user to select which one of three USB
removable flash media (Internal SD Card, Internal Drive Key,
or External Drive Key) to boot first if multiple media are
present. Please note that the system is limited to two bootable
removable USB flash media, and due to the order in which USB
devices are enumerated, the system will not boot to the
external drive key even if selected as first when all three
types of media are present. In addition, this option does not
override the device boot order selected in the Standard Boot
Order (IPL) option.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Removable Flash Media Boot Sequence

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Enables the HW portion of a feature that allows systems 
to be protected against malicious code and viruses. In 
combination with an OS that supports this feature, memory 
is marked as non-executable unless the location explicitly 
contains executable code. Some viruses attempt to insert 
and execute code from non-executable memory locations. These 
attacks are intercepted and an exception is raised.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: No-Execute Memory Protection

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
When enabled, a Virtual Machine Manager supporting this feature 
can utilize hardware capabilities provided by Intel`s 
Virtualization Technology.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Intel(R) Virtualization Technology

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature allows disabling of logical processor cores on 
processors supporting Intel`s Hyper-Threading Technology 
This option may improve overall performance for applications
that will benefit from higher processor core count.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Intel(R) Hyperthreading Options

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature allows disabling of processor cores using Intel`s
Core Multi-Processing (CMP) Technology.  This option allows
disabling a specific number of the cores on each physical processor.
This option has the following potential uses:  Reduce processor 
power usage and potentially improve performance/watt with 
some applications; improve overall performance for applications 
that will benefit from higher performance cores rather than more 
processing cores; address issues with software that is licensed 
on a per-core basis. The value entered should be the number of 
enabled cores per socket.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Processor Core Disable (Intel Core Select)

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Turbo Boost Technology is a processor feature which allows
the processor to transition to a higher frequency than the
processor`s rated speed if the processor has available
power headroom and is within temperature specifications.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Intel(R) Turbo Boost Technology

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
When enabled, a Virtual Machine Manager supporting this feature 
can utilize hardware capabilities provided by Intel`s 
Virtualization Technology for Directed I/O.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Intel(R) VT-d

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
By default, the System ROM will disable the embedded video
controller when an optional video controller is installed
in the system. This option allows for the embedded video
controller to remain enabled so that iLO remote video still
functions or for dual head video support.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Video Options

options.name: Optional Video Primary, Embedded Video Disabled
Optional Video Primary, Embedded Video Secondary
Embedded Video Primary, Optional Video Secondary

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature allows the user to select the fan cooling solution 
for the system. Optimal cooling provides the most efficient 
solution by configuring fan speeds to the minimum required to 
provide adequately cooling. Increased Cooling will run fans at 
higher speeds to provide additional cooling. Increased Cooling 
should be selected when non-HP storage controllers are cabled to 
the embedded hard drive cage, or if the system is experiencing 
thermal issues that cannot be resolved in another manner.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Thermal Configuration

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the locking of the Asset Tag information
When set to lock, the Asset Tag will NOT be erased if the
default system settings are restored.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Asset Tag Protection

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option provides the capability to enable or disable SR-IOV 
(Single Root I/O Virtualization).
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: SR-IOV

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Multi Processor Specification Table/APIC Setting    
is used for interrupt routing. Certain unsupported  
operating systems may require setting the Multi     
Processor Specification Table Mode to APIC Disabled.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: MPS Table Mode

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText: Allows generating an NMI via the NMI button/jumper.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: NMI Debug Button

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Controls the Virtual Install Disk. The Virtual
Install Disk may contain drivers specific to this server
that an OS may use during installation.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Virtual Install Disk

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the user to disable the default PCI Bus
setting where each expansion slot is provided an extra
PCI Bus number. By default, the System ROM will pad one
PCI bus per expansion slot to allow expansion cards
with PCI-PCI bridges to not effect current bus numbering
schemes. Disabling this option works around issues with
certain expansion cards. It is not recommended this option
be disabled unless a specific issue has been seen.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: PCI Bus Padding Options

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows disabling the display of the Logo during
system boot. This is an aesthetic modification only. This
option does not affect system boot times.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Power-On Logo

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the disabling of the POST One
Time Boot F11 Prompt.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: F11 Boot Menu Prompt

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option selects the level of Consistent Device Naming.
On supported operating systems, NIC ports will be named
based on their location in the system.
"CDN Support for LOMs Only" will only name Embedded NICs
and FlexibleLOMs (not NICs in slots). Note that existing
NIC connections will retain their original name until
reinstalled under the OS environment.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Consistent Device Naming

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the user to disable the Network Boot 
Retry Support. By default, the System ROM will attempt to 
boot the Network device (i.e. PXE device) up to 20 times
before falling through to the next IPL Device.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Network Boot Retry Support

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option controls the System ROM logic of retrying 
bootable devices listed in the Standard Boot Order (IPL) 
if no bootable media is found. When set to Enabled, the 
System ROM will reset the platform after one attempt 
through the Standard Boot Order (IPL). When disabled, 
the System ROM will continually loop through the 
Standard Boot Order (IPL).
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Reset on Boot Device Not Found

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows a user to disable HP Expansion Cards 
from delaying during POST and waiting on user input to 
enter Expansion Card Setup Utilities.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: HP Option ROM Prompting

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the disabling of a processor 
prefetch feature.  In very limited cases, setting this
option to Disabled may improve performance.
In the vast majority of cases, the default value of Enabled
provides better performance.  Users should only disable
this option after performing application benchmarking to
verify improved performance in their environment.
This option is sometimes called the MLC Streamer Prefetcher.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: HW Prefetcher

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the disabling of a processor 
prefetch feature.  In very limited cases, setting this
option to Disabled may improve performance.
In the vast majority of cases, the default value of Enabled
provides better performance.  Users should only disable
this option after performing application benchmarking to
verify improved performance in their environment.
This option is sometimes called the MLC Spatial Prefetcher.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Adjacent Sector Prefetch

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the disabling of a processor prefetch
feature. In very limited cases, setting this option to
Disabled may improve performance. In the vast majority of
cases, the default value of Enabled provides better
performance. Users should only disable this option after
performing application benchmarking to verify improved
performance in their environment.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: DCU Streamer Prefetcher

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the disabling of a processor prefetch
feature. In very limited cases, setting this option to
Disabled may improve performance. In the vast majority of
cases, the default value of Enabled provides better
performance. Users should only disable this option after
performing application benchmarking to verify improved
performance in their environment.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: DCU IP Prefetcher

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Enabling Node Interleaving disables the NUMA architecture
properties of this system.  All operating systems supported
by this platform support NUMA architectures.  In the majority
of cases, optimum performance is obtained by disabling Node
Interleaving.  When this option is enabled, memory addresses
will be interleaved across the memory installed for each
processor.  Some workloads may see improved performance when
this option is enabled.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Node Interleaving

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option controls the ability for the processor to accelerate
I/O operations by reducing the number of I/O related memory
accesses. This option should increase I/O performance while
reducing system power and I/O latency.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Data Direct I/O

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option enables certain networking devices to improve
performance by utilizing Intel`s DMA engine to offload network
activity. Please consult network adapater documentation for
more details.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Intel NIC DMA Channels

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Combined Channel Mode provides maximum data protection by
allowing multiple-bit memory errors to be corrected in certain
instances not possible in normal Advanced ECC Modes. Please
see user documentation for memory installation rules
for Combined Channel Mode.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Memory Channel Mode

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This ACPI SLIT (System Locality Information Table) describes the
relative access times between processors, memory subsystems, and
I/O subsystems. Operating Systems that support the SLIT can use
this information to improve performance by allocating resources
and workloads more efficiently.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: ACPI SLIT Preferences

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
With the System Management Driver loaded, the Automatic 
Server Recovery feature allows the system to automatically 
reboot if the server locks up.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: ASR Status

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
If Automatic Server Recovery is enabled, this selection 
sets the time to wait before rebooting the server in the 
event of an operating system crash or server lockup.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: ASR Timeout

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
When Enabled, the system will attempt a graceful shutdown
due to fan failures or removals which takes the system to
below the minimum number of required fans or when the
temperature increases beyond a pre-set threshold.  When
Disabled, the system will continue to operate until the
temperature reaches a point where the system must be powered
off immediately to prevent damage to hardware components.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Thermal Shutdown

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Wake-On-LAN (WOL) allows the server to be
powered on remotely when it receives a special packet.
This feature requires a NIC, NIC driver and Operating
System that are WOL-capable.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Wake-On LAN

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
POST Error Response:
Enabled: halt at an F1 prompt.
Disabled: bypass the F1 prompt.
Delayed: delay at the F1 prompt for 20 seconds.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: POST F1 Prompt

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Disabling this feature disables the momentary power
button functionality. This feature does not affect the
4 second power button override. Also, this feature does
not affect the remote power control functionality.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Power Button

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature configures the server to automatically power
on when AC power is applied to the system. By default, 
the system will return to its previous power state when 
AC power is restored after an AC power loss. This option
allows overriding this behavior such that the system will
either power on or remain off when power is reapplied.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Automatic Power-On

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature will delay the server from turning on for the 
desired time. Pressing the power button, using the iLO 4 
Virtual Power Button, Wake-ON LAN events and RTC Wake-up 
events will override the delay and immediately turn on the 
server.  This allows staggering when servers power-up 
after a power loss to prevent power usage spikes.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Power-On Delay

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText: Input a message to be viewed during POST.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Custom POST Message

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the enabling of the Trusted Platform Module and
BIOS secure startup. When enabled, the TPM is fully functional.
When disabled, the TPM will be visible to software, but functionality
will be limited.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: TPM Functionality

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option provides the ability to hide the TPM from the operating
system. When the TPM is hidden, BIOS secure startup is disabled,
and the TPM will not respond to any commands from software. This
option is intended to be used to remove the TPM feature from the
system without removing the actual hardware.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: TPM Visibility

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows enabling the BIOS to measure the PCI/PCI-e
expansion (Option) ROM code and store that measurement into the
TPM. Operating systems or validation software which utilizes the
measurements stored in the TPM may now detect modifications to 
PCI/PCI-e expansion ROM versions.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: TPM Expansion ROM Measuring

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the user to reset the TPM to factory settings,
clearing any assigned passwords, keys, or ownership data. Clearing
the TPM may prevent the server from booting to a TPM-aware operating
system if the operating system was utilizing the TPM`s measurements.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: TPM Clear

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature allows for video and keystrokes to be redirected
through the serial port prior to OS boot.  This feature may
interfere with non-terminal devices attached to the
serial port.  Set it to Disabled in this case.
This option is only supported when the Serial Port settings 
are set to COM 1 or COM 2. BIOS Serial Console is not supported
when the Serial Port is configured for COM 3.
This feature is not supported under RBSU in Japanese mode.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: BIOS Serial Console Port

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This is the transfer rate at which data will be transmitted
through the serial port.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: BIOS Serial Console Baud Rate

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This is a Windows Server 2008 feature that allows for emergency
management console to be redirected through the serial port
When making this selection for redirecting EMS through a network
connection, there are two options:
1) If using ILO, select the value (COM1 or COM2)
that corresponds to the resources assigned to the Virtual Serial
Port in the System Options menu of RBSU.
2) When redirecting EMS through a physical serial port, select the
value (COM1 or COM2) which corresponds to the resources assigned
to the embedded serial ports in the System Options menu of RBSU.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: EMS Console

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
Auto Mode enables CLI mode automatically for ROM embedded
utilites if the system detects a console connection through 
the serial port.  Command-Line Mode always enables CLI mode 
for ROM embedded utilities.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: BIOS Interface Mode

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
- Balanced Power and Performance:  Provides the optimum settings to
  maximize power savings with minimal impact to performance for most
  Operating Systems and applications.
- Minimum Power Usage:  Enables power reduction mechanisms that may
  negatively affect performance.  This mode will guarantee a lower
  maximum power usage by the system.
- Maximum Performance:  Disables all power management options that
  may negatively affect performance.
- Custom: Automatically selected when individual power settings are
  modified. Setting this option here does not change anything.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: HP Power Profile

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature configures the Power Regulator for ProLiant support:
- HP Dynamic Power Savings Mode: Automatically varies processor
  speed and power usage based on processor utilization. Allows
  reducing overall power consumption with little or no impact to
  performance. Does not require OS support.
- HP Static Low Power Mode: Reduces processor speed and power
  usage. Guarantees a lower maximum power usage for the system.
  Performance impacts will be greater for environments with
  higher processor utilization.
- HP Static High Performance Mode: Processors will run in their
  maximum power/performance state at all times regardless of
  the OS power managment policy.
- OS Control Mode: Processors will run in their maximum
  power/performance state at all times unless the OS enables
  a power management policy.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: HP Power Regulator

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature enables placing the Quick Path Interconnect (QPI) links
into a low power state when the links are not being utilized.
This will lower power usage with minimal performance impact.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Intel QPI Link Power Management

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the user to set the QPI Link frequency to 
a lower speed. Running at a lower frequency may reduce 
power consumption but may also impact system performance.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Intel QPI Link Frequency

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
The QPI link between 2 processors has been tuned to provide the
best performance for all known applications.
The Balanced option is the default since it provides the best
performance for nearly all conventional customer applications and
benchmarks. The optimized for I/O option has
been shown to increase bandwidth from I/O devices such as GPUs
that rely on direct access to system memory.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: QPI Bandwidth Optimization (RTID)

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature selects the processor`s lowest idle core power state
(C-State) which the operating system will utilize. The higher the
C-State, the lower the power usage of that idle state (Core C6 is
the lowest power idle core state supported by the processor).
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Minimum Processor Idle Power Core State

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature selects the processor`s lowest idle package power
state (C-state) which is enabled. The processor will automatically
transition into package C-states based on the Core C-states which
cores on the processor have transitioned to. The higher the
package C-state, the lower the power usage of that idle package
state (Package C6 (retention) is the lowest power idle package
state supported by the processor).
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Minimum Processor Idle Power Package State

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option configures several processor subsystems to optimize
the processor`s performance and power usage. Balanced Performance
provides optimum power efficiency and is recommended for most
environments. Maximum Performance Mode should be used for
environments that require the highest performance and lowest
latency but are not sensitive to power consumption. Power Savings
Mode should only be used in environments that are power sensitive
and are willing to accept reduced performance.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Energy/Performance Bias

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature allows configuring the memory system to run memory 
at a lower maximum speed than what is supported by the installed
processor and DIMM configuration. Setting this option to Auto 
will configure the system to run memory at the maximum speed
supported by the system`s configuration.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Maximum Memory Bus Frequency

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This feature allows modifying the level of interleaving for
which the memory system will be configured. Typically, 
higher levels of memory interleaving will result in maximum
performance.  However, reducing the level of interleaving can
result in power savings.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Channel Interleaving

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
If a PCI-Express device does not run properly at the speed that it
was designed for, lowering the speed in which the device is running
may address the problem. This option allows lowering the maximum
PCI-express speed the server will allow PCI-express devices to
operate at and may be useful in addressing issues with problematic
PCI-express devices. Setting this value to Maximum Supported will
configure the platform to run at the maximum speed supported by the
platform or the PCI-e device (whichever is lower).
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Maximum PCI Express Speed

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
The Dynamic Power Savings Mode feature allows the System ROM to
control processor performance and power states depending on the 
processor workload.
This option allows configuring the response time for switching 
between these states.
 - The Fast setting is optimal for most workloads where low latency 
    response to an increase in processor demand is a requirement.
 - The Slow setting is optimal for some workloads where a longer
    latency response to increases in processing demand is an 
    acceptable tradeoff for reduced power consumption.
Selecting this option may have a negative performance impact 
depending on the workload.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Dynamic Power Savings Mode Response

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
For Operating Systems that support the Processor Clocking Control
(PCC) Interface, enabling this option allows the Operating System
to request processor frequency changes even when the server has the
Power Regulator option configured for Dynamic Power Savings Mode.
For Operating Systems that do not support the PCC Interface or when
the Power Regulator Mode is not configured for Dynamic Power Savings
Mode, this option has no impact to system operation.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Collaborative Power Control

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the user to disable the System ROM Power
Calibration feature that is executed during the boot process.
When disabled, the user can expect faster boot times but will
not be able to enable a Dynamic Power Cap until this feature
is re-enabled.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Dynamic Power Capping Functionality

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option allows the user to increase the voltage of LVDIMMs
to 1.5V to allow memory to operate at an increased frequency
(in certain configurations). If configured to Optimized for Power
LVDIMMs will run at 1.35V even if this requires memory to run at a
lower frequency. Note: The system will not allow 1.35V operation
unless all installed DIMMs in the system are LVDIMMs.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: DIMM Voltage Preference

serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.category: Power Management Options//Advanced Power Management Options
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.helpText:
This option configures several memory parameters to optimize
the memory subsystems performance and power usage. Balanced 
provides optimum power efficiency and is recommended for 
most environments. Maximum Performance Mode should be used
for environments that require the highest performance and/or
lowest latency but are not sensitive to power consumption.
serverHardwareTypeUri_ADD_biosSettings.name: Memory Power Savings Mode
